    <td width='100%' valign='top' align='left'><font face='Arial' size='2'><br><br>In terms of healing
    pets it is an interesting situation.  Magicians have the highest mana-efficiency for
    instant pet heals.  However, Magician's also are masters of 'Chain Casting'
    being able to summon an entirely new pet with full health for low mana.  </font><p><font
    face='Arial' size='2'>In prolonged fights, a Necromancer can use their more powerful and
    efficient pact spell on their pet whilst also draining health back from the enemy with
    Bond of Death.  This can keep a Necromancer pet lasting a long time.  Add to
    this the new lifetap proc's being given to the 44+ Necromancer pets and we have a pet that
    can be kept alive for a long time.</font></p>
    <p><font face='Arial' size='2'>Enchanters do not have a direct heal, but rather a
    cost-free shieldskin.  This will absorb spell and melee damage, and can be used to
    keep an animation alive in desperate circumstances.  Considering the high mana cost
    of buffing this is often very worthwhile for an Enchanter.  Furthermore, since
    animations cannot be called off and have the least hitpoints of all, Enchanters have the
    short end of the stick in terms of keeping their summoned helpers hitting.  This is
    due to the fact that an animation is designed to be purely an assistant to a group in
    combat providing extra-taunt off the Enchanter and some good damage to boot.</font></p>
    <p><strong><font face='Arial' size='2'>Other Things of Interest</font></strong></p>
    <p><font face='Arial' size='2'>Some other things to note in balancing pets.</font></p>
    <p><font face='Arial' size='2'>Necromancers have the ability to snare (darkness series)
    and fear to reverse kite.  They also have powerful DoT's which when combined with a
    good pet are incredibly powerful.  Indeed it is this reverse kite method for which
    Necromancers are famous, being able to solo some of the most powerful creatures alone in
    outdoor areas.  They also have the ability to root targets while they resummon new
    pets if they are stuck in a confined dungeon area.  Their pets are high level, with a
    high max damage output and good to medium level hitpoints.</font></p>
    <p><font face='Arial' size='2'>Magicians do not have the ability to reverse kite anywhere
    near as well since they cannot slow down the feared prey.  Nor do they have powerful
    DoT's.  Magician's can however summon new weapons for their pets at any time, have a
    wide variety in pets with varying base attack rates, health and spells.  They also
    have powerful damage shields for tanking pets.  Since they do not have root,
    Magicians rely on the ability to resummon new pets quickly and at low mana cost to replace
    those which fall in combat.</font></p>
    <p><font face='Arial' size='2'>Enchanters suffer the same problem as magicians when it
    comes to reverse kiting.  The key to Enchanter pet fighting is in their ability to
    slow the enemies attacks down.  With Shiftless Deeds on the enemy the Enchanter pet
    turns into a serious lawnmower.  Mix into this a DD or two, a stun here or there, the
    ability to mesmerise extra mobs, or even the current mob should the pet die, and you have
    a very powerful combination.  The only major drawback for enchanter pets is that they
    cannot control their animations at all, and they are very weak.  This fits well
    within the vision for enchanters though as a supplementary class that was designed to work
    as an enhancement to groups more than in a solo environment.</font></p>
    <p><font face='Arial' size='2'><strong>Conclusion</strong></font></p>
    <p><font face='Arial' size='2'>I think the patch change has not had an overall 
    adverse effect on game balance.  Magicians are definitely the masters of pets now,
    but they were always meant to be from a game vision point of view.  Necromancers pets
    still attack faster than Magician pets, and in the right circumstances are much easier to
    keep alive.  Magicians are simply much more mana efficient when it comes to pets,
    buffing them, shielding them, and equipping them.  Enchanter pets are truly becoming
    what was intended, a simple 'assistant' in battle.  </font></p>
    <p><font face='Arial' size='2'>I don't think the patch has made Necromancer's weak in any
    way.  Whilst it is certainly a downgrade in their performance and has made them
    slightly weaker in terms of raw melee damage, this has also effected Enchanters as well.
      Necromancers are being compensated with a pet that heals easier, and also a new
    series of spells to make grouping more balanced, though what the real effect of these will
    be is unknown.  Enchanters have not received any compensation for the change, perhaps
    at some point an examination could be had into increasing slightly the hitpoint of
    animations to allow them to be a little more group friendly.  There is always the
    faint chance that they might one day get commands, but that seems to be a big case of
    wishful thinking. </font></p>
    <p><font face='Arial' size='2'>All in all, a patch which has I think brought some balance
    to caster pets.  There still remains the issue of Pet Power v Melee classes, but
    that's an altogether different debate which I will leave for another day.</font></p>
